The question does not provide any info about the classes you are using. I had to guess how the classes should look like. 

Here are two approaches. The first one uses custom classes `Item` and `Scenario` which is my best guess on how your actual classes look like. The second approach uses `Map`s.

**Option 1:**

Using custom classes:

    public class Item {
        
        private final char id;
        
        private final double[] values;
        
        public Item(char id, double... values) {
            this.id = id;
            this.values = values;
        }
        
        public final char getId() {
            return id;
        }
        
        public final double[] getValues() {
            return values;
        }
        
        public final double getTotalValue() {
            return Arrays.stream(values).sum();
        }
        
        @Override
        public String toString() {
            return &quot;[id=&quot; + id + &quot;, values=&quot; + Arrays.toString(values) + &quot;]&quot;;
        }
        
    }
    
    public class Scenario {
        
        private final Item[] items;
        
        public Scenario(Item... items) {
            this.items = items;
        }
        
        public final Item[] getItems() {
            return items;
        }
        
        public final double getTotalValue() {
            return Arrays.stream(items).mapToDouble(Item::getTotalValue).sum();
        }
        
        @Override
        public String toString() {
            return Arrays.toString(items);
        }
        
    }
        
    public static final Scenario getHighestScenario(Scenario... scenarios) {
        return Arrays.stream(scenarios)
                .sorted(Comparator.comparingDouble(Scenario::getTotalValue).reversed())
                .findFirst().orElse(null);
    }

